us hopes asian countries free from mad cow scare
( agence france - presse , manila , 14th ) - u . s . agricultural officials said that asian countries will have safe to eat us beef even though a mad cow disease broke out in the united states last month .
safety quarantine has been stepped up immediately after the united states found the first case of mad cow disease , although japan , south korea and other asian countries have immediately banned or restricted the import of us beef .
us officials said tuesday that the units concerned had already carried out an investigation into the spread of mad cow disease and had not exported beef at the beginning of the outbreak . moreover , relevant units have been stepping up quarantine in the past 10 years to strictly prevent the outbreak of mad cow disease .
mad cow disease also claims to be suffering from brain disease ( bo e - e ) in relation to the form of the human brain disorder , known as " creutzfeldt - jd " .
" we are very optimistic that these asian countries will further reduce the scope of the existing ban in the coming month or so , " said the director of the us department of agriculture 's asian affairs department green light when holding a press conference in manila .
green added , " we have assured all asian countries of the safety of us beef . "
he said the japanese delegation was visiting the united states to learn more about us measures to prevent mad cow disease .
south korea steps up quarantine measures against bird flu
( agence france - presse , seoul , 14th ) - south korean officials said south korea reported new bird flu outbreaks after nine days of peace . south korea has stepped up quarantine efforts to prevent further spread of bird flu .
a quarantine zone has been set up near a chicken farm located in the leung shan area 300 kilometers southeast of seoul , the agriculture ministry said .
bird flu viruses have been detected in this region by health officials on monday .
this is the first time in nine days that south korea has confirmed the discovery of a bird flu virus .
last month , bird flu broke out in 15 parts of south korea , forcing authorities to cull and cull nearly two - million chickens and ducks . this highly contagious poultry disease is apparently under control .
" we culled all chickens in the epidemic area and strictly restricted the movement of these poultry , " said kim chang - soo , director of the animal health section of the ministry of health in south korea .
the emergence of new bird flu cases has prompted south korean government officials to strengthen quarantine in other areas .
" the bird flu virus can survive for two weeks in dust , and can survive at least 35 days in poultry droppings , " kim said .
bush managed to maintain free trade zone plan at the americas summit
( agence france - presse , monterrey , mexico , 13 th ) u . s . president bush is very ambitious to promote the establishment of a free trade area of the americas next year . he reluctantly supported the leaders of 33 other countries at the summit meeting of the americas today .
however , the united states failed to include anti - corruption clauses in the final communique on how to fight the increasingly serious poverty in the western hemisphere .
the scope of the free trade area of the americas , from alaska and the south to argentina , claims to be the largest free trade zone in the world , with a total market population of about 800 - million people and a total output of 1.3 - trillion us dollars .
however , in his speech at the close of the two - day summit , argentine president teheran attacked the us plan , saying the issue of the americas could not be resolved merely by the establishment of a free trade zone .
brazil , the largest economic country in south america , and venezuela , the main oil supplier of the united states , are all opposed to putting the issue of the free trade area of the americas on the summit agenda . however , after heated discussions , leaders of various countries announced that they would agree to complete the negotiations on the establishment of the free trade area of the americas by january 2005 .
