continuous labor cut is bound to affect economic production in eu and japan
( agence france - presse , dakar , switzerland , 19 th ) a research report released by the world economic forum ( wef ) and consulting firm ( u . s . firm ) today pointed out that due to the contraction of the workforce , the output value of the european union ( eu ) will reduce by nearly half of the global output value by 2050 .
in contrast , rich labor in developing countries such as india and china should be able to help boost economic growth .
" growth in labor force and productivity will determine economic output , " said shmans , executive director of the huyue company .
in countries where the labor shortage is large , the supply of commodities and labor services may not meet the demand and living standards . "
the report , entitled " living a happier life : the economic impact of ageing society , " pointed out that medical progress and growth in life expectancy would definitely have a direct impact on economic production compared with the continuous rise in labour force and retired population ( especially in developed countries ) .
in response to the report , a statement issued by the study pointed out , " the current population statistics and economic trends remain unchanged . by the year 2050 , the proportion of the european union in the global gross economic output will be reduced from the current 18 percent to 10 percent . "
the statement also warned that " japan 's share of the ratio will shrink from 8 percent to 4 percent . "
