31 qin tombs discovered in fengxiangjiang county , shaanxi
xinhua news agency , xi'an , january 15 ( iron ma ) in the past , the historical circle always believed that the palace of the sun jiatou village in fengzhang county , shaanxi province had become the venue for royal worshipping only after the qin people moved to the yongcheng city . however , the shaanxi archaeological institute recently discovered 31 tombs in this palace , and it is expected to change this saying .
in order to coordinate with a company in baokai city to build a plant at the site of the ruins , shaanxi archaeological research institute conducted archaeological prospecting there , and discovered 31 qin tombs from the west to the spring and autumn period of about 20,000 square meters in emergency use .
through the shaanxi yongcheng archaeological team 's clean - up and excavation of these ancient tombs , a total of over 40,000 pieces of cultural relics including bronze ware and pottery were unearthed .
one of the qin tombs is a dead and two - horse burial pit beside the tomb .
fifteen pieces of bronze ware and pottery were unearthed from the burial . there were bronze ware , pots , and hammers on the ground .
among them , the bronze medallists are well - produced and well - dressed , and have maintained the casting style of the western zhou bronze ware .
judging from the items accompanying the burial , the owner of the tomb is the qin nobles in the late qin dynasty .
experts therefore speculated that there should be a huge ancient tombs nearby .
the accident found that the relocation of qin capital and the arrangement of yongcheng city during the qin dynasty were of great historical value .
tian yafqi , assistant researcher at shaanxi archaeological research institute and director of the yongcheng archaeological team , said that historical circles had always believed that the palace dianming district in nantou village was the place where the qin people moved from the qin dynasty to the xihan royal palace to carry out major worshipping activities .
this discovery shows that before moving to yongcheng , this place was the feng yi of the western zhou dynasty , which had experienced several times of prosperity .
